README.md
     1→# sps
     3→> [!WARNING]
     4→> I will scrap this project in favor of sps v2 some time in the future (when v2 is built and ready which might take a while). The reason is that I am planning to
     5→> implement my own packaging system, my own version of atomic installs / updated complete with automatic snapshots and full, down to single package rollbacks +
     6→> automatic cve checks and some other stuffs. After a lot of thinking and looking at Homebrew's architecture I've come to the conclusion that I do not like it (burn
     7→> me for it ;). Defining my own build system will allow for a more performant and maintainable system in the long run. (Just a bit anxious about how to host packages
     8→> / do all the repo stuff. Like really anxious but I'll figure it out)
     9→>
    10→> Another reason is that I made some choices on internal architecture in the beginning that I have come to see as suboptimal but can not easily refactor so this will
    11→> allow me to go for the better option right from the get go (go for rx/tx for status propagation from the start, build the core fully async etc.)
    12→>
    13→> I have just made the repo for sps2 public. There is no repositories yet and core systems still do not work and need debugging. However it passes ci and the
    14→> architecture is largely in place. I will have to create a automatic upstream tracking system, automatic builds and create build scripts for the most important
    15→> tools too still + bootstrap the repositories.
    16→>
    17→> Never done that so if anyone has experience with that stuff help is appreciated. 
    18→>
    19→> For repo architecture I will probably go for a classic unix style repo format with cloudflare r2 and automatic replication to multiple regions. Well that is quite
    20→> far out. Still it is coming along well, just built my first package with it. Found some small issues with install right after and am working on those now.
    21→>
    22→> https://github.com/alexykn/sps2 Take a look if you want!
    23→
    24→
    25→sps is a next‑generation, Rust‑powered package manager inspired by Homebrew. It installs and manages:
    26→
    27→- **Formulae:** command‑line tools, libraries, and languages
    28→- **Casks:** desktop applications and related artifacts on macOS
    29→
    30→> _ARM only for now, might add x86 support eventually_
